          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--label)">Flight Header</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">The sticky header remains visible while scrolling. <strong>Flight ID</strong> turns <span style="color:var(--sys-yellow)">yellow</span> when FCIR/ASAP is active. Tap <strong>OUT</strong> or <strong>IN</strong> to edit — changing OUT automatically recalculates all downstream ETAs. The <strong>ETOPS</strong> block (ETOPS flights only) shows the authorisation and elapsed time to ETOPS entry.</p>

          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--label)" style="margin-top:var(--sp4)">Departure Subcard</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>ATIS</strong>: Tap the letter box to enter the ATIS identifier. The notes field accepts free text or Pencil input.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>PARK</strong>: Departure gate or stand. Free text.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>OEI</strong>: Tap to select the departure runway from the TLR picker. The applicable EFP is displayed; SPECIAL procedures show the full text; SEE CO CHART runways open a notepad. Falls back to a free-text field when no TLR is present.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 14px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>STAB</strong>: Stabilizer trim. Always crew-entered.</p>

          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--label)">OFP Fuel Subcard</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Block</strong>: Colour-coded by TOGW margin — <span style="color:var(--sys-green)">green</span> &gt;1,000 · <span style="color:var(--sys-yellow)">yellow</span> 500–1,000 · <span style="color:var(--sys-red)">red</span> &lt;500 lbs/kgs from structural limit.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>MIN · FRES · GA</strong>: Parsed from OFP. GA is always crew-entered.</p>

          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--label)" style="margin-top:var(--sp4)">Notes Section</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Airport status dots</strong>: Every airport on the release shown with a colour dot (green/yellow/red) and abbreviated issue tags. Based on the same evaluation as the full Airport cards.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>DDG</strong>: MEL/CDL items parsed from the OFP. 25-series (cabin/NEF) items are filtered out. Items with TLR cross-references show colour-coded badges (Takeoff / Landing / Both).</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Overflights</strong>: Permit numbers. Only shown when present.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Curfews</strong>: Airports with a curfew window within 120 min of ETA. Parsed from Company NOTAMs.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Perishables</strong>: Banner shown when OFP indicates perishable cargo on board.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Notes</strong>: Free-text notepad. Keyboard and Apple Pencil Scribble. Saved per flight.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- BRIEFING — ENROUTE -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">Briefing — Enroute Phase</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Enter the actual <strong>OFF</strong> time (wheels-up, HHMM UTC) to populate the computed event schedule. The right column is a free-text scratchpad for notes, calculations, or Apple Pencil drawings.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>E.ENT</strong> (ETOPS flights): Estimated time of ETOPS airspace entry, calculated from OFF + elapsed time parsed from the OFP.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>RDA</strong> (RDA/redispatch flights): Redispatch Authorisation time — 2 hours before the POR. The point at which the crew must have confirmed fuel state to continue under the redispatch plan.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>POR</strong>: Point of Redispatch waypoint and estimated time. Includes <strong>MINF</strong> — the minimum fuel required on board at the POR to continue to destination.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>CO RPT</strong>: Company position report schedule at 4-hour intervals from OFF. Reports that fall within the RDA–POR window are shown struck through — the POR report covers that window.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- BRIEFING — DESCENT -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">Briefing — Descent Phase</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">The Arrival subcard brings together the information needed for the approach brief in one place.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Arrival airport status</strong>: A colour dot and issue tags for the selected arrival airport, evaluated using the same rules as the full Airport cards. Tap the ICAO code to change the arrival airport — useful if the planned destination has changed. The picker lists all airports on the release except the origin, each with a live status dot.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>ATIS &amp; PARK</strong>: Independent from the departure fields. Same Pencil/keyboard input.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 5px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>TLR Landing items</strong>: Any DDG items with a TLR Remarks cross-reference for Landing or Takeoff+Landing are displayed here automatically — below the Parking field — so they are at hand for the arrival brief without navigating to the Notes section.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Arrival Fuel subcard</strong>: REMF, ALT 1, FRES, and GA at destination. REMF and ALT 1 are parsed from the OFP; GA is crew-entered.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- AIRPORTS TAB -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">Airports Tab — Detail</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Each airport card shows the role (ORIG, DEST, DEST ALT, EN ROUTE ALT, TKOF ALT, CFS ALT), ETA, and a colour-coded status badge from combined weather and NOTAM evaluation.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Tappable alert items</strong>: Each alert row with a chevron <span style="color:var(--label3)">›</span> can be tapped to view the exact NOTAM entry or TAF group that triggered it. The raw text is displayed in full with proper word-wrapping so all information is visible.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Weather categories</strong> (FOM §7.1.31): <span style="color:var(--sys-green)">Open</span> — ceiling ≥3,000ft and vis ≥5SM · <span style="color:var(--sys-yellow)">Operational</span> — ceiling 1,000–3,000ft or vis 3–5SM · <span style="color:var(--sys-red)">Instruments</span> — ceiling 600–1,000ft or vis 1–3SM · <span style="color:var(--sys-red)">🔴</span> — ceiling &lt;600ft or vis &lt;1SM. The alert row shows the actual ceiling and visibility values.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>WX Window</strong>: For standard airports the evaluation window is ETA ±1 hour. For CFS alternates the window is the exact WX WINDOW published in the OFP Critical Fuel Scenario table.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Weather &amp; NOTAMs</strong>: Auto-populated from the OFP weather pages. Tap any card header to open the edit fields and paste additional or updated data.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)"><strong>Curfew row</strong>: When Company NOTAMs contain a curfew window, a tappable row shows the window and proximity to ETA, colour-coded by how close the ETA falls.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ETOPS / CFS -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">ETOPS &amp; Critical Fuel Scenario</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">On ETOPS flights, the OFP contains a <strong>Critical Fuel Scenario (CFS)</strong> section listing ETOPS alternate airports with ETP pairs and OFP-calculated WX windows. These airports are added automatically alongside standard alternates and receive full airport cards with weather and NOTAM evaluation.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Each CFS airport uses its OFP-published WX WINDOW rather than a computed ETA ±1 hour window. Return and continue (GO) airport roles are identified per ETP scenario. ETP waypoint coordinates appear in the Alternates tab.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">The ETOPS authorisation (e.g. <em>ETOPS 60/180</em>) and ETOPS ENTRY elapsed time are parsed from the OFP and displayed in the Briefing tab flight header in tint colour.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- EDITING VALUES -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">Editing Values</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Any value displayed in <span style="color:var(--tint);text-decoration:underline dotted">tinted dotted-underline text</span> is editable. Tap it to open an edit panel. Editing <strong>OUT</strong> recalculates all downstream ETAs. Editing <strong>OFF</strong> (actual wheels-up time) recalculates the IN time using OFP trip time.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Airport weather and NOTAM fields on each airport card are editable — tap the card header to expand the input fields.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- FCIR/ASAP -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">FCIR / ASAP Toggle</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">The <strong>FCIR/ASAP</strong> toggle is in the top navigation bar of the flight screen, to the right of the <strong>?</strong> help icon. When active, the flight ID turns <span style="color:var(--sys-yellow);font-weight:600">yellow</span>, and the flight row in the Saved Flights list stays highlighted in yellow across sessions.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Activating the toggle reveals a <strong>FCIR/ASAP Narrative</strong> notepad on every phase. Use it to record event details (description, times, observations). Tap the copy icon in the narrative header to copy the text to clipboard.</p>
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)" style="color:var(--sys-red);font-weight:600">⚠ Do not delete this flight entry until the FCIR/ASAP report has been submitted. The flight cannot be deleted while the toggle is ON.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">To allow deletion: open the flight, turn off the FCIR/ASAP toggle, then return to Saved Flights.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DATA & PRIVACY -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header">Data &amp; Privacy</div>
      <div class="cell-group">
        <div class="cell" style="cursor:default;display:block;padding:var(--sp3) var(--sp4)">
          <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">All data is stored locally on this device in your browser's storage. No data is sent to any server. Each browser profile has its own private data store — two crew members using the same physical iPad but different Safari profiles will have completely separate flight records.</p>
          <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;color:var(--label2)">Up to 25 flights are retained. Older flights are removed automatically when the limit is reached. Deleting the app or clearing browser data will remove all saved flights.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>


<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     SERVICE WORKER REGISTRATION — Offline-first PWA
     Registered last so it never blocks app startup.
     The SW pre-caches the app shell + pdf.js CDN assets
     so the app works fully in airplane mode after first load.
     ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<script>
if ('serviceWorker' in navigator) {
  // Defer until after the page is fully interactive
  window.addEventListener('load', () => {
    navigator.serviceWorker.register('./sw.js', { scope: './' })
      .then(reg => {
        // Check for updates whenever the app regains focus
        // (covers the "closed and reopened" scenario)
        document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', () => {
          if (document.visibilityState === 'visible') reg.update();
        });
      })
      .catch(err => console.warn('SW registration failed:', err));
  });
}
</script>
